channel.title: UM portfolio
channel.description:
This page is intended to reflect my creative work in the areas of experimental music composition, sound art & design and field recordings:
- Ugnė (Davai Bėgam)

<input
				type="text"
				class="mf-input "
				id="mf-input-text-444fe81a"
				name="mf-name"
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Name *`) } "
									onInput=${parent.handleChange}
					onBlur=${parent.handleChange}
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-name'] ? 'true' : 'false'}
					ref=${el =>{
												parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":true,"expression":"null"}, el)
					}}
								/>
							<${validation.ErrorMessage}
					errors=${validation.errors}
					name="mf-name"
					as=${html``}
					/>
			<input 
				type="email" 
				defaultValue="" 
				class="mf-input " 
				id="mf-input-email-5975a22" 
				name="mf-email" 
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Email *`) } " 
				onBlur=${parent.handleChange} onFocus=${parent.handleChange} aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-email'] ? 'true' : 'false' } 
				ref=${el=> parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","emailMessage":"Please enter a valid Email address","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":true,"expression":"null"}, el)}
							/>
						<${validation.ErrorMessage} 
				errors=${validation.errors} 
				name="mf-email" 
				as=${html``}
			/>
			<input
				type="text"
				class="mf-input "
				id="mf-input-text-119a7a1c"
				name="mf-Subject"
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Your Subject *`) } "
									onInput=${parent.handleChange}
					onBlur=${parent.handleChange}
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-Subject'] ? 'true' : 'false'}
					ref=${el =>{
												parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":true,"expression":"null"}, el)
					}}
								/>
							<${validation.ErrorMessage}
					errors=${validation.errors}
					name="mf-Subject"
					as=${html``}
					/>
			<textarea id="mf-input-text-area-2feb70ac"
				name="mf-textarea" 
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Your Message `) } "
				cols="30" rows="10"
									onInput=${ parent.handleChange }
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-textarea'] ? 'true' : 'false'}
					ref=${ el => parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":false,"expression":"null"}, el)}
								></textarea>
							<${validation.ErrorMessage}
					errors=${validation.errors}
					name="mf-textarea"
					as=${html``}
					/>
								<input type="hidden" name="mf-hidden-input-name" value="mf_hidden_input_value" ref=${parent.setDefault} />
							<button type="submit" id="">
					${ parent.decodeEntities(`Send Message`) } 
				</button>

					onBlur=${parent.handleChange}
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-name'] ? 'true' : 'false'}

						<${validation.ErrorMessage}

<input
				type="text"
				class="mf-input "
				id="mf-input-text-5b3f240"
				name="mf-name"
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Name *`) } "
									onInput=${parent.handleChange}
					onBlur=${parent.handleChange}
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-name'] ? 'true' : 'false'}
					ref=${el =>{
												parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":true,"expression":"null"}, el)
					}}
								/>
							<${validation.ErrorMessage}
					errors=${validation.errors}
					name="mf-name"
					as=${html``}
					/>
			<input 
				type="email" 
				defaultValue="" 
				class="mf-input " 
				id="mf-input-email-65124dd4" 
				name="mf-email" 
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Email *`) } " 
				onBlur=${parent.handleChange} onFocus=${parent.handleChange} aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-email'] ? 'true' : 'false' } 
				ref=${el=> parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","emailMessage":"Please enter a valid Email address","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":true,"expression":"null"}, el)}
							/>
						<${validation.ErrorMessage} 
				errors=${validation.errors} 
				name="mf-email" 
				as=${html``}
			/>
			<input
				type="text"
				class="mf-input "
				id="mf-input-text-1e8447e2"
				name="mf-Subject"
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Your Subject *`) } "
									onInput=${parent.handleChange}
					onBlur=${parent.handleChange}
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-Subject'] ? 'true' : 'false'}
					ref=${el =>{
												parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":true,"expression":"null"}, el)
					}}
								/>
							<${validation.ErrorMessage}
					errors=${validation.errors}
					name="mf-Subject"
					as=${html``}
					/>
			<textarea id="mf-input-text-area-585d67d"
				name="mf-textarea" 
				placeholder="${ parent.decodeEntities(`Your Message `) } "
				cols="30" rows="10"
									onInput=${ parent.handleChange }
					aria-invalid=${validation.errors['mf-textarea'] ? 'true' : 'false'}
					ref=${ el => parent.activateValidation({"message":"This field is required.","minLength":1,"maxLength":"","type":"none","required":false,"expression":"null"}, el)}
								></textarea>
							<${validation.ErrorMessage}
					errors=${validation.errors}
					name="mf-textarea"
					as=${html``}
					/>
								<input type="hidden" name="mf-hidden-input-name" value="mf_hidden_input_value" ref=${parent.setDefault} />
							<button type="submit" id="">
					${ parent.decodeEntities(`Send Message`) } 
				</button>

a:5:{s:20:"mf-hidden-input-name";s:21:"mf_hidden_input_value";s:7:"mf-name";s:5:"Diana";s:8:"mf-email";s:23:"dianacruz.mkt@gmail.com";s:10:"mf-Subject";s:40:"Re: Improve your website traffic and SEO";s:11:"mf-textarea";s:419:"Hi team,

I came across your Website, when searching on Google and noticed that you do not show in the organic listings.

Our main focus will be to help generate more sales & online traffic.

We can place your website on Google's 1st page. We will improve your website’s position on Google and get more traffic.

If interested, kindly provide me your name, phone number, and email.

Your sincerely,
Diana
";}

a:5:{s:20:"mf-hidden-input-name";s:21:"mf_hidden_input_value";s:7:"mf-name";s:10:"Ella Flora";s:8:"mf-email";s:22:"ellafloramkt@gmail.com";s:10:"mf-Subject";s:32:"Increase Traffic to your website";s:11:"mf-textarea";s:662:"Hello,

I'm Ella Flora and I work for a Digital Marketing Agency providing service globally. I've been researching your industry and found your website.

I noticed a few issues that may be hindering your potential ranking on Google and your ability to generate online inquiries and sales. I've compiled a multi-page analysis of your website addressing all of these errors.

Would you like my Director of Digital Marketing to send you a report? Either way, it is free of cost. It is my hope that he can discuss some of these findings in greater detail. Is there a good time for you to talk next week?

Thanks and best regards,
Ella Flora
Website Analyst";}

SUMMARY

Ugnė Makselytė

Sound artist, electronic and experimental music composer, sound designer, field recordings enthusiast and environmental explorer based in Kaunas, Lithuania.

EXPERIENCE

2016

Archivist

Kunstkamera, Vilnius

2020

Research Assistant (RA)

theatre research in preparation in the Phd dissertation of Justinas Kalinauskas, Kaunas

2022-2023

Assistant sound engineer

music festival "Braille Satelite'', Varėna

2023

Assistant sound engineer

recording studio "Lapės Records", Kaunas

2023

Assistant sound engineer

Radio Station "Cashmere Radio", Berlin

2023

Music & Sound Art teacher

Secondary School "Kardokai Nature School", Kardokai

EDUCATION

2018 - 2020

Philosophy BA & Art History and Critique minor

Vytautas Magnus University

2020 - 2023

Music Technologies BA

Kaunas University of Technology

2022 - 2023

Musicology & Composition, Erasmus +

Aristotle University of Thessaloniki

Facebook Soundcloud Bandcamp

AUDIO FAIRY TALE

THE EYES OF SIRIUS

FAIRY TALE "THE EYES OF SIRIUS"

Text, music, sound design, audio production, voice - Ugnė Makselytė

Mastering - Bartoš Eiliakas

Released by IKRA 2022

The project was realized by personal funds.

 

links:

audio fairytale:

https://brkncrcts.bandcamp.com/album/sirijaus-akys

text (lithuanian):

https://www.slinktys.lt/Projektai/Literaturines-slinktys-2020/Rasytojai/ugne-makselyte.htmla

 

---
Sirius's Eyes is an original fairy tale by Ugne Makselytė, written in 2020 and published in the literary collection Literaturinės slinktys. After two years author independedly created and produced the audio version of this piece.

*The sound design and music in the story was created using homemade samples, field recordings and DIY instruments. Content was found in mynthology, dreams and forests*

STORY

"Sirius's Eyes is an audio fairy tale written by Ugne Makselytė in 2022. The story is inspired by folklore, mythology and rituals of different cultures. The most inspiration comes from the tradition of the initiation ritual in various shamanistic cultures. The creative process is also strongly shaped by the author's dreams and visions that arose during meditation.
The tale is about Sirius, a person who lost his eyes during a dream. After becoming blind, Sirius went to the forest, hoping to regain his lost eyes with the help of the spirits of the forest. Sirius encounters a variety of forest creatures and has to overcome a number of obstacles related to spirit transformations.
Eventually Sirius finds his eyes in the burning ears of the Blue Forest Cat. Will he be able to get them back out and regain his sight?

 

 

Listen on bandcamp

experimental l ambient l field recording

FENCES (TVOROS)

MUSIC ALBUM "FENCES"

Music - Ugnė Makselytė

Cover art - Marija Brusokaitė

link:

https://davaidegam.bandcamp.com/album/tvoros

ABOUT

Tvoros is an album of experimental ambient music created in Kaunas in 2021. The creative process was focused on sonic explorations of fences and various industrial metal surfaces in Kaunas, Žaliakalnis district. This district is considered special because of its exceptional modernist architecture, which is listed as a UNESCO heritage site. Thus, the entire Žaliakalnis district is full of private houses built between the wars. Each of them is unique in both appearance and spirit, as are the metal fences that surround the houses. Each fence has a unique timbre and most of them, in fact, even creak quite a lot - that is how old these fences are. The intention of the search for sounds in the fences was to find meditative, sacred and therapeutic sounds, with the idea that refreshment and calm can be found not only in nature but also in the urban environment where most of us spend our daily lives. Was this attempt of creating meditative music from fences a success? Well, maybe it came out a bit dark. However, most of the fences are rusty, heavy, huge. But by recording the fences in different ways (with pjezo, omnidirectional microphones, and so on), it became clear that each one of those fences is a whole separate sonic universe, which wouldn't take one album to express. After all, it is important to mention that this experiment took place during a quarantine period, when we were all isolated and severely confined to our immediate environment. So this sonor research on fences was also a great way for the author to keep herself from going completely insane.

Tvoros is an album of experimental ambient music created in Kaunas in 2021. The creative process was focused on sonic explorations of fences and various industrial metal surfaces in Kaunas, \u017daliakalnis district. This district is considered special because of its exceptional modernist architecture, which is listed as a UNESCO heritage site. Thus, the entire \u017daliakalnis district is full of private houses built between the wars. Each of them is unique in both appearance and spirit, as are the metal fences that surround the houses. Each fence has a unique timbre and most of them, in fact, even creak quite a lot - that is how old these fences are. The intention of the search for sounds in the fences was to find meditative, sacred and therapeutic sounds, with the idea that refreshment and calm can be found not only in nature but also in the urban environment where most of us spend our daily lives. Was this attempt of creating meditative music from fences a success? Well, maybe it came out a bit dark. However, most of the fences are rusty, heavy, huge. But by recording the fences in different ways (with pjezo, omnidirectional microphones, and so on), it became clear that each one of those fences is a whole separate sonic universe, which wouldn't take one album to express. After all, it is important to mention that this experiment took place during a quarantine period, when we were all isolated and severely confined to our immediate environment. So this sonor research on fences was also a great way for the author to keep herself from going completely insane.<\/p>","text_color":"#FFFFFFC7","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_family":"Inter","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":16,"sizes":[]},"typography_font_weight":"400","typography_line_height":{"unit":"em","size":1.560000000000000053290705182007513940334320068359375,"sizes":[]},"typography_word_spacing":{"unit":"em","size":"","sizes":[]},"_margin":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"20","left":"0","isLinked":false},"__globals__":{"text_color":"","typography_typography":""},"pa_condition_repeater":[]},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":true},{"id":"77db915d","elType":"widget","settings":{"image":{"id":38,"url":"https:\/\/ugnemakselyte.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/10\/icon2.png"},"width":{"unit":"px","size":37,"sizes":[]},"width_tablet":{"unit":"px","size":"","sizes":[]},"width_mobile":{"unit":"px","size":"","sizes":[]},"_position":"absolute","_offset_x":{"unit":"%","size":48.5,"sizes":[]},"_offset_x_tablet":{"unit":"%","size":"","sizes":[]},"_offset_x_mobile":{"unit":"%","size":41,"sizes":[]},"pa_condition_repeater":[]},"elements":[],"widgetType":"image"}],"isInner":true}],"isInner":true}],"isInner":false},{"id":"6871a0e","elType":"container","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"f6b394b","elType":"widget","settings":{"link":{"url":"https:\/\/soundcloud.com\/davai-begam\/tvoros1","is_external":"","nofollow":"","custom_attributes":""}},"elements":[],"widgetType":"audio"}],"isInner":false},{"id":"429e8f7","elType":"container","settings":{"flex_direction":"column"},"elements":[{"id":"32e9f6b","elType":"widget","settings":{"text":"listen to full album","link":{"url":"https:\/\/davaidegam.bandcamp.com\/album\/tvoros","is_external":"on","nofollow":"","custom_attributes":""}},"elements":[],"widgetType":"button"}],"isInner":false}]

encoded.__cdata: This two-part EP was made during the summer holidays in 2021 in the village of Pilvingiai. Like most other Lithuanian villages, it is surrounded by forests and fields and is located far from the city. Being in nature, especially after the quarantine in the city, was the inspiration for the new field recording project. Birds, croaking frogs, running water and other wonderful sounds from Dzūkija are intertwined with samples of tools and vocal elements recorded in the barn on this release.

encoded.__cdata:
This EP consists of a two-part soundscape composition project created in 2022.

The soundscapes are created from field recordings made while traveling through the Balkan region.

Places visited: North Macedonia: Skopje Kosovo: Pristina Bosnia and Herzegovina: Sarajevo, Banja Luka Slovenia: Ljublijana Greece: Thessaloniki.

The journey was made by hitchhiking with a dear friend Justas.

The aim of the work is basically just to reveal the experience of culture and everyday life in the Balkan region from the perspective of a traveler. The collages were created quite spontaneously, aiming not to over-process the sound of the original field recordings, but reflecting on their composition in the context of each other. The collages were composed to reflect the inner experience of the journey, which reveals itself as a fusion of experiences of different places in the mind of the listener/traveler. In the end, even though at least a few countries and certainly more than a couple of cities have been visited, the memories of the journey emerge as merged and complex images. For example, the dripping water from the gutter in Thessaloniki, together with fragments of a recorded conversation on a
bus in Skopje.

Field Recordings, creative idea, production, composition, visual artwork: Ugnė Makselytė

Travel comrade: Justas Korskovas

2022

Listen on BandCamp

encoded.__cdata:
This release features sounds that were an integral part of a sound installation created during the summer of 2022.

The interactive installation aimed to draw attention to the details of our everyday experiences and the beauty of human perception. It was designed to be a user-friendly tool for exploring order in chaos and finding beauty in seemingly unpleasant things.

Unfortunately, after the exhibition in the parking lot of the Music Department at Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, the sound installation disappeared under mysterious circumstances. But the focus is now on the sounds themselves. You will hear seven short pieces based on recordings of ASMR videos and some electroacoustic experimental improvisations.

During the project, author remained conscious of the environmental details while expressing the texture of different materials through sound. The goal was to remind us that the more external details we let into our lives, the richer our experience becomes.

And in the end, it's clear that order and beauty exist even in the seemingly mundane, as exemplified by the flashlight shining down the throat.

INSTALATION

 

The installation was composed of two sound controllers and a microphone. The controllers were two boxes that displayed the artist's collages of photographs of her own body parts, retouched and used to create symmetrical visual compositions. They were also decorated with various textures created using paint, glue, and organic details such as shells and dried grasses. The controllers were controlled by potentiometers and distance-responsive infrared sensors. The microphone installed in the installation captured the soundscape of the underground car park of the Music Faculty of the Aristotle University of Thessaloniki.

The photo-collaged controller allowed the listener to independently mix the recorded sound collages created by the author, which were mainly composed of ASMR sound recordings, vocal improvisations, and various sonic experiments simmilar to the ones of the FOLEY to life. The listener could control the volume level of the sound collages by operating four potentiometers, thus creating an individual and spontaneous listening experience.

Another controller, decorated with shells and paint, controlled the microphone. It was equipped with a single potentiometer to control the volume level of the microphone, which directly captured the environment, while two distance-responsive sensors controlled effects that processed the input of the microphone.

The listener could thus control the delay and vibrato effects with their own hands, resulting in an interesting deconstruction of the soundscape of the recorded environment. Finally, the listeners had the opportunity to mix live and spontaneous sound collages created by the author with live ambient sounds and processed effects.

Instalation was created as a part of a university course "Interactive Music Systems" at the Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Music Department.

 

Instalation ".Perception": Ugnė Makselytė

Professor and the curator of the final exhibition: Dimitris Maronidis

 

ALBUM

The sound pieces used as material for the interactive sound installation were released as a cassette by an independent experimental music label "Right Now" records by Tadas Greičiūnas.

Cassette is distributed by TapeKiosk

 

 

 

Listen on BandCamp (self release) Cassette from Tape Kiosk

encoded.__cdata:
Ecology is a project born out of the author's ambition to combine field recordings and noise music with the principles of more conventional music composition (like four-voice harmony and a certain form of the piece). It is a composition of field recordings created in 2023, with the material collected in Lithuania, Greece, Italy, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Macedonia, and Bulgaria.
This work was the creative part of the author's final Bachelor's project in 2023, at Kaunas University of Technology, graduating from the Music Technology program.

A little quote from the personal description of this piece:

"First of all, I'd like to present the structure of the piece which was supposed to correspond to what we know as the rondo structure of the music piece. 

[Rondo is a musical form, that emerged in the Baroque period that contains a principal theme (sometimes called the "refrain") that alternates with one or more contrasting themes, very generally called "episodes". In this way, the repetitive, circular structure of the piece is achieved.]

And the choice of this structural form came up after the recognition of this form naturally appeared in one particular field recording used in this piece. It was a field recording made in Milan during a metro journey. Since the recording itself consists of a repeated organization of sounds, it was very natural to apply the recording to the basis of the rondo form of composition. The part of the recording between the journeys - the opening and closing of the door, reflecting a stop at a subway station - was left as a refrain. The sound of acceleration that follows becomes a kind of bridge to the next episode of the composition - a collage of field recordings.

The second experimental approach to the musicalisation of the field recordings was an attempt to sort all of the audio material into categories corresponding to the idea of four-part harmony. Based on the dominant frequency band in the spectrum of the recording, the recordings were categorized into soprano, alto, tenor, and bass. Then, by composing them together, I tried to find a way to harmonize them according to the basic rules of harmony. However, I was not able to achieve this task in a way that sounded natural. Thus, this idea was only applied conditionally, as a kind of guideline to encourage constant reflection on the balance of the sounds divided into four voices and their aesthetic interaction. 

In my exploration of field recordings, I also delved into the tonality of the sounds and attempted to identify any possible harmonic functions within the composition. To simplify it, we can understand the most basic harmonic functions as the relationships between three main tonal points: the tonic, subdominant, and dominant. Identifying these pitches is crucial in determining the tonality and key of the piece. For this particular work, I selected three field recordings in which the pitch was identifiable:

The tonic sound is a church bell recording (F) 

The subdominant sound is the scream of a child falling off a scooter in a park (Bflat) 

The dominant sound is the sound of a speeding car (C)

So, following this idea, an attempt was made to compose the field recordings as if the whole work was tonal and written in the key of F. In the end of the piece you will also hear an element of vocal improvisation with a church bell as its accompaniment.

Throughout the piece, each stop represents a sonic journey into a unique acoustic environment created by various field recordings that are unrelated to each other. Although the collages that follow the 'refrain' may appear chaotic and unexpected at first, they ultimately contribute to the repetitive structure of the composition. 

In conclusion, it's probably unlikely that you can perceive the harmony by ear in this piece. However, creating a general balance between the various sounds that comprise the piece was the goal, and using idea of harmony-based composition helped me achieve that."

title.__cdata: The Voices of Women. Stories from Kaunas textile industry

encoded.__cdata:
The sound installation was created as a collaboration with the artist, researcher, and curator Agnė Bagdžiūnaitė. Installation was a part of audio - visual exhibition under the same name at the Kaunas Picture Galery in 2023.

"The exhibition reveals the multi-voiced narratives of women who worked in Kaunas textile factories during the late Soviet era and the first decade of independence. It is a polyphonic narrative: people's stories, and memoirs surrounded by the soundscape of artist Ugne Makselytė. Although the historical textile factories in Kaunas have disappeared, their interiors, the sounds of their machines, the smells they emitted, the chemistry of the fabric dyes, and the images of the steam have remained in the imagination, dreams, and memories of the women who worked there as a background. In it, the women's lives, the twists and turns of their careers, and the relationships of the work team are intertwined, intertwined, or interrupted, just as they are today, but in a different way.

The stories of eight women who worked at Drobė, Kauno Audiniai, and Litex - ten hours of documentary collected by the exhibition curator Agnė Bagdžiūnaitė - have been transformed into a 55-minute audio composition. It is a kind of fiction, like radio theatre, a play about work and feelings towards work, machines, and materials.

For their sincere stories, openness, and trust, the creators of the exhibition are grateful to former Kaunas textile workers Janina Gobužienė, Elea Šliužaitė, Brone Valienė, Brone Jastromskienė, Agne Macke, Aldona Laucaityte, Irena Rinkšeliene, and Aušrute Juškevičienė.

 


Agnė Bagdžiūnaitė - artist, curator, researcher.
Her practice and research are based on the methodologies of human history, feminist ethnography, and the theory of social reproduction. Agnė is currently working as a curator at Kaunas Artists' House, and participates in the activities of the social centre Emma, the 1st of May Trade Union (G1PS), and the leftist media platform Life is Too Precious.

Ugnė Makselytė graduated from KTU Music Technology in Kaunas. She works in the fields of experimental electronic, dance, and ambient music, in soundscape composition, and interdisciplinary projects combining sound art and literature. Ugnė is interested in the experience of everyday ritual through soundscape, outdoor recording art and acoustic ecology, dance, movement, and poetry music, as well as various vocal experiments in compositions.

The exhibition is presented by the community platform Small Stories, which since 2017 has been exploring industrial memory and labor histories in the exhibition series Big Industry.

 

 


Women's voices - Janina Gobužienė, Elė Šliužaitė, Bronė Valienė, Bronė Jastromskienė, Agnė Mackė, Aldona Laucaitytė, Irena Rinkšelienė, Aušrutė Juškevičienė.

Sound design - Ugnė Makselytė and Agnė Bagdžiūnaitė.
Objects - Agnė Bagdžiūnaitė.
Graphic design - Julija Tolvaišytė-Leonavičienė
Sound technician Karolis Lasys.
Curator of the exhibition Agnė Bagdžiūnaitė.
The organizer of the exhibition.
Vytautas, Aldona, Žilvinas R., Virginija J., Kaunas House of Artists."

 

Link to the galery page

encoded.__cdata:
It was a collaboration with other artists participating in the Kaunas Biennial project, who took part in the Kaunas Capital of Culture program (KEKS 2022). The project aimed to create an interactive augmented reality experience that included both physical explorations of the space and audio-visual works created by collaborating artists from different artistic fields: musicians, writers, graphic designers, actors, and painters. The idea and narrative of the project were based on the industrial tales of the famous Lithuanian writer Julius Kaupas about the city of Kaunas.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MYbt_QqyVwU&ab_channel=KaunasBiennial

"The project places newly created tales about Kaunas and its inhabitants in the very centre of the city. The tales have been created and depicted by nine Kaunas artists and creators, based on Julius Kaupas's book Doctor Kripštukas in Hell. This book is a collection of fairy tales that intertwines philosophical thoughts, humour, fairy tale motifs, wisdom and eternal values, and brings to life the secrets and beauty of Kaunas.

Co-authors of the idea.
Jokūbas Bateika, Tadas Zaranka, Karolis Skiparis, Loreta Valantiejienė, Jolanta Vilija Galdikaitė, Ieva Trišauskaitė, Marius Šablevičius, Ugnė Makselytė, Vytautas Mikalauskas.
Illustrator: Agnė Žiūkaitė

More about the project at www.kaunopasakos.lt and @kaunopasakos Instagram account.

Part of the EU Creative Europe 2014-2020 Platforms Project "Magic Carpets". Sponsored by the Lithuanian Council for Culture."

encoded.__cdata:
This work can be considered the first electroacoustic work to use ambient, experimental techniques, DIY instruments and field recordings and tapes. Much of the creative material for this work was created by recording family gatherings and going through old video archives. The ambient part was created by stretching various samples of recorded instruments such as piano, voice and percussion, as well as several field recordings made in the vicinity of the Ignalina nuclear power plant in Lithuania.
The composition of the work is absolutely symmetrical. The two movements share exactly the same foot. In fact, the second movement is identical to the first, but played in reverse. The whole concept is based on a failed attempt at meditation, which the composer has experienced on several occasions (especially during quarantine). This experience could be described in words as an uncomfortable silence, generating a plethora of memories that tend to be experienced in reverse: starting with the newer ones and working backwards until the consciousness reaches the earlier ones.

N: We don't know how much the medication helped, how much was more subconscious work...

A: But you know, the main thing is that the subconscious is completely out of control... For example, I can't control it. Completely.

N: In this case you don't need anything really, just some lexotonil. It frees you from anxiety, and anxiety is the main cause of your situation.... The anxiety is the root cause of your anxiety.

Listen on Bandcamp

encoded.__cdata:
Taking a part in a colllective release (as Davai Bėgam) made by the label Tapekiosk reflecting the scene of Kaunas experimental music.

This collection documents contemporary experimental sound artists from Kaunas city and district.

encoded.__cdata:
The Rite for the Black Sun is a synthesis of music, text, dance and theatre based on the 20th century French playwright Antonin Artaud's radio play "Pour en finir avec le jugement de dieu". The play is a critique of the socio-political phenomena of its time and a blow to the dogmas of Western thought and the hegemony of rational reason that have been established over the centuries. In response to the text, the performance is like a game on the edge of absurdity, an attempt to rethink the meanings of beauty, ugliness, reason and madness.

Dance (butoh): Saulė Paulikaitė
Music: Arūnas Periokas
Text (translation and spoken word performance): Ugnė Makselytė

2019

 

The work was performed in lithuanian festivals "Funikulierius" and "Sapfo" as well as in the Museum of Devils in Kaunas and X20 social space in Vilnius.

Link to the audio Link to the text (lithuanian) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l0n22sjq6Nk&list=LL&index=544&ab_channel=E8Tone

encoded.__cdata:
Hell Rides - This is a collaborative performance initiated by the young generation of Lithuanian poet Patricija Gudeikaitė. The work combines butoh dance improvisation by Saulė Paulikaitė, experimental electronic music composed by Ugnė Makselytė and a text read during the performance - the uatoric poems of Patricija Gudeikaitė.

Texts: Patricija Gudeikaitė

Butoh dance improvisation: Saulė Paulikaitė

Music: Ugnė Makselytė

Costume and make up: Ash Paulikaitė

2023

"Every substance has a Shadow -repressed aspects that we would rather not acknowledge exist. The poetic performance "hell rides" is an attempt to challenge the dark underbelly of the subconscious - secret desires, lust, volatility, suspicion and irrationality. Using Patricija Gudeikaitė's poetry, Japanese Butoh dance performed by Saulė Paulikaitė and experimental music by Ugne Makselytė, the poet will turn to the shadow side of the personality, walk on the forbidden margins, create poetic mise-en-scenes, and question the integrity of personality."

Patricija Gudeikaitė "Contact":

"Patricija Gudeikaitė's poetry conveys, in precise, laconic sentences, situations where there is no longer a distinction between what is real and the phantasms of the unconscious, phobias, paranoia, obsessive thoughts. This is not traditional confessional poetry, as the main artistic device is a mask, which can be an intertext or a fictional creature. The poems are reminiscent of performance scenes, mini-plays in which the director and the actor, the victim and the murderer, are the speaker or the spoken. During the performance, both the actors and the audience forget, at least for a moment, that everything that happens on stage is fake, that it is fiction. Reading Patricia's poems, literature overcomes reality, everyday logic, rationality. Hence their cathartic power." - Literary critic Dr. Virginija Cibarauskė

 

Read more about the texts Excerpt from a musical composition

encoded.__cdata:
KAITrA is a duo formed by Ugne Makselytė and Saule Paulikaitė specially for the Yaga Gathering 2021 festival. The project combined Butoh dance improvisation by Saulė Paulikaitė and electronic music by Ugnė Makselytė, blending elements of Lithuanian folklore with electronic dance music. The idea of combining Butoh, electronic dance music and Lithuanian folklore was born spontaneously, inspired by Gilles Deleuze's idea of the Body Without Organs, which led to the search for eclectic and unexpected creative solutions, such as the fusion of Baltic folklore motifs with the eccentric Japanese butoh dance. The artists wanted to try out a form that would not be limited to a clear representation, but would freely incorporate different elements from both artists' experiences and backgrounds, and thus embody the idea of a fundamental change as the basis of our existence.

photos by Tomas Šaltis, 2021

encoded.__cdata:
SPAM is an improvisational experimental music collective that originated at the University of Aristotle in Thessaloniki. The collective was founded and is currently curated by Danae Stefanou, who is a composer, researcher, and performer working at AUTH. Although the composition of the collective is constantly changing, its essence and purpose remain the same over the years, which is to explore and cultivate experimental sound art through various artistic practices. These practices include collective improvisation, DIY instrument making and application, creation of graphic and textual scores, and their application in music, discussions, field events, sound walks, active listening meditations inspired by the ideas of Pauline Oliveros and her colleagues. In 2022, I had the honor of working with and being part of this collective. Together, we created and released a DIY zine of graphic and text scores. Additionally, we worked on the collective piece "how would I know τι να κανω", which is currently available on Bandcamp.

"In January 2023, σπΑΜ* sat around a table, and worked on the production of a zero-skills zine. The zine contained printouts and handwritten fragments of scores by group members, documenting private and shared thoughts gathered during a typically dystopian autumn and winter in Thessaloniki, Greece. After the end of the meeting, it was laid out, printed and xeroxed using only the scant & broken university resources available at the School of Music Studies, Thermi Campus, AUTH.

This one-track album consists of a single, short audio piece. The piece is an audio document of that meeting, the making of our first Spamzine. It is also the only online documentation of Spamzine's existence.

Spamzine itself is not to be found digitally. Copies have been making their way across the world, exchanging hands in the form of gifts, subjecting themselves to all kinds of reprints and modifications, and finding themselves waiting in the most unlikely locations, until a friendly stranger picks them up and decides to perform them.

Should you find a copy, please make music with it. Please keep the zine physical-only, and don't digitize / don't upload anywhere in its entirety. But feel free to send us your zine performances, or just say hi.

The zine is in Greek, but also partly in English, because τι να κανουμε.

Τrack includes compositions by:
Dimitris Georgakainas
Theofanis Kamariaris
Ugne Makselyte
Ayis Vlahos

Mixed, edited and processed by Ugne Makselyte

σ.π.Α.Μ.* χειμώνας 2022 - σ.π.Α.Μ.* winter 2022:
Δέσποινα Αθανασοπούλου - Despina Athanassopoulou
Άγις Βλάχος - Ayis Vlahos
Κασσάνδρα Δαλλού - Cassandra Dallou
Δημήτρης (Τζίμης) Γεωργάκαινας - Jimmy Georgakainas
Θεοφάνης Καμαριάρης - Theofanis Kamariaris
Παναγιώτης Κυριαζής - Panagiotis Kyriazis
Θωμάς Λαζάρου - Thomas Lazarou
Ugne Makselyte - Ούγκνε Μαξελύτε
Πηνελόπη Νικάκη - Penelope Nikaki
Μελίνα Παπαγιάννη - Melina Papagianni
Χρήστος Παπαδόπουλος - Christos Papadopoulos
Νίκος Σιδηρόπουλος - Nick Sidiropoulos
Δανάη Στεφάνου - Danae Stefanou
Φανή Τσιτσιάμη - Fani Tsitsiami

*σύνολα πειραματικής & αυτοσχεδιαζόμενης μουσικής

σ.π.Α.Μ.* is pronounced "spam".
It is an acronym.
It stands for Experimental and Improvised Music Ensembles.
So now you know." 

released January 30, 2023

Listen on BandCamp

encoded.__cdata:
Soundtrack for a short film by lithuanian driector Laura Udra "Black Black Night"

Year: 2022
Duration: 25'
Genre: fiction

DIRECTOR & WRITER Laura Udra
PRODUCER Natalija Butylkina
CINEMATOGRAPHY Nikolas Verseckas
EDITING Martynas Duškinas
SOUND DESIGNER Rūta Girnytė
COMPOSERS Ignas Andriuskevicius, Ugnė Makselytė
PRODUCTION DESIGNER Agnė Ragelytė
COSTUME DESIGNER Diana Barkovskaja

title.__cdata: Human Mystery Equals That One of an Insect’ (Litauisches Kino Goes Berlin, 2021)

encoded.__cdata:
Participation in the Lithuanian Film Festival Berlin "Litauisches Kino Goes Berlin, 2021" with the experimental improvisational music collective IKRA from Kaunas. During the creative process, the artists created alternative soundtracks for Wladyslaw Starewicz animated films, which were later performed live in Berlin during a film screening. My contribution to the overall creative process was that I made an alternative soundtrack for  Wladyslaw Starewicz film "Insects' Christmas", 1913.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GlEeQ-NzBeY&ab_channel=Ugn%C4%97Makselyt%C4%97 event in 2021
